title: MisinformationEffect
published: Blank, H., & Launay, C. (2014). How to protect eyewitness memory against the misinformation effect: A meta-analysis of post-warning studies.¬†Journal of Applied Research in Memory and Cognition, 3, 377-88. doi:10.1016/j.jarmac.2014.03.005
description:
The 'misinformation effect' is a well-known phenomenon in the psychology of memory. In its classical version, it refers to negative effects of post-event misinformation on memory for previously witnessed events (i.e. memory for event details becomes less accurate and misleading details are remembered instead), but it has been investigated outside the eyewitness context as well. 

In a number of studies, researchers have tried to reduce the misinformation effect through warnings about the (potential) presence of misinformation. This has been tried either before or after the introduction of misinformation, but the latter (i.e. post-warnings) is more practically relevant, as it is rarely possible to pre-warn people about misinformation. 

The featured meta-analysis investigated the effectiveness of post-warnings (compared to no-postwarning control conditions) in terms of (1) improving the accuracy of memory for witnessed event details and (2) reducing the reporting of misinformation in memory tests. It also explored if the beneficial effects of post-warnings depend on additional variables (moderators).
